Tech: Intel CEO Pat Gelsinger has been ousted by the board after a period of poor performance, signaling potential changes in the company's strategy[2]. The Nasdaq reached a new record high to start December trading, driven by strong performance in the tech sector[2]. NVIDIA, the world's largest company by market cap, released earnings results that were closely watched by investors[1]. Additionally, the U.S. is set to launch its third semiconductor crackdown on China in three years, restricting exports to 140 companies, which could impact semiconductor toolmakers[2].

Manufacturing: Stellantis CEO Carlos Tavares has unexpectedly resigned amid "different views" between the executive and the board of directors, potentially impacting the company's future direction and performance[2]. The manufacturing sector may also be affected by President-elect Trump's social media posts calling for 25% tariffs on goods from Canada and Mexico, as well as an additional 10% tariff on products from China[1].

Energy: Oil prices rose on Monday, boosted by strong Chinese factory data and renewed Israel-Lebanon clashes despite a ceasefire, stoking Middle East tensions[2]. WTI oil traded lower earlier as Israel and Lebanon reportedly agreed to a ceasefire, but the situation remains volatile[1].

